    abstract = {Previous research has documented significantly larger income-related gaps in children’s early cognitive development in the US compared to the UK, Canada and Australia (Bradbury et al., 2011). This paper investigates how far this is a result if a more unequal income distribution in the US. We show that, although incomes are more unequal in the US than elsewhere, nevertheless a given income differential is associated with larger disparities in child development there than in the three comparator countries. In particular, high-income families in the US appear able to translate the same amount of financial resources into greater cognitive advantages relative to the middle than those in the other countries. We compare inequalities in other kinds of family characteristics and show that middle-income families in the US are disadvantaged by relatively higher levels of maternal employment and less access to preschool than groups with comparable incomes in the other countries.},
