    abstract = {Most research on intergenerational income mobility measures economic status in each generation by relying on either a single-year income observation or a short-term average over multiple years. Adopting a life course perspective, we focus on income dynamics over the individual’s life course and examine the association of income trajectories across generations. We propose a group-based trajectory approach to characterize population heterogeneity in income trajectories. This approach assigns individuals into several distinct trajectory groups, as compared to the conventional approach that assumes a continuous distribution of trajectories among individuals. We estimate the trajectory memberships of parents and offspring and their interdependence in terms of social mobility probabilities from one generation to the next. Using data from the Panel Study of Income Dynamics, our results show significant differences in intergenerational income association among groups that experienced divergent income trajectories over the life course.},
