    abstract = {Although kin marriage is widely practiced in the Middle East, the rationales motivating kin endogamy have not been widely tested. This study assesses evidence for two economic rationales underlying kin marriage using the 2006 and 2012 Egypt Labor Market Panel Surveys. The first rationale involves an attempt to consolidate family property through the marriage of relatives. A second rationale for kin marriage is the fact that less costly marriage assets are exchanged when relatives wed. Using a number of measures, we find no evidence that women whose parents owned land or enterprises (or whose parents owned more land or enterprises of higher value) had higher odds of entering into kin unions, contrary to expectations based on the literature. We do find, however, that women who wed relatives reported lower matrimonial expenditures and higher proportional expenditures by the groom and his family, thus lending support to the second rationale for kin marriage.},
