    abstract = {We use the rich and unexploited Spanish 1991 Socio-Demographic (ESD) retrospective survey (N 157,000) to investigate the demographic, social and economic factors that have shaped intergenerational co-residence in Spain among the cohorts born between 1900 and 1960. This world’s unique original dataset was reformatted into a person-years file to allow for life-course analysis with multiple time varying co-variates (i.e. availability of living kin and the partnership, migration, education and work life-course trajectories). Our models neatly assess the multiple factors that have either reinforced or weakened intergenerational co-residence over time. First, opportunities for intergenerational co-residence have expanded dramatically due to improving parental survival and declining fertility. Second, marriage and migration have diminished co-residence. And, third, net of the previous factors, the normative change towards less co-residence becomes extremely salient, progressing in parallel with the structural modernization of the Spanish society in terms of educational, occupational and activity status.},
