    abstract = {This paper examines the the relationship between family size and intra-family financial transfers from adults to their aging parents. I use data on China's one-child policy. This policy exogenously affects the number of children in Chinese families, which solves the statistical problem that childbearing is endogenous. I show that family size is positively correlated with whether aging parents in China receives monetary supports from their adult children. However, the number of children has no significant effect on the amount of support the parents receive, which is consistent with my further finding that on average, the amount of monetary support (to aging parents) per child is greater in families with fewer children.},
